  Suggestions (how I'd build it)

  - Self-contained mock "tour" routes per role (/tour/member, /tour/gym, /tour/instructor) that render a faux app shell (header +
  body) pre-filled with sample data, and a coachmark engine steps through elements — swapping the mock "screen" as you advance (step
  4 = schedule mock, step 7 = forum mock…). No real navigation, never empty, works before login, and renders responsively at real
  Tailwind breakpoints. This upgrades your existing /tour demos rather than fighting the "new user has no data / empty real pages"
  problem.
  - Coachmark engine: I'd use driver.js — tiny (~5kb), framework-agnostic, gives the spotlight + popover + arrows + next/back +
  keyboard nav, and themes cleanly to your tokens (brand-red, Space Grotesk). react-joyride is the React-native alternative if you
  prefer.
  - Data-driven steps: one config array per role — { screen, selector, title, body, placement } — so steps are easy to edit and we
  can localize/extend later.
  - Mobile handling: the real nav collapses to a hamburger on mobile, so mobile steps that point at nav need a "open the menu first"
  hook. driver.js supports onHighlightStarted for this. (This is the main responsive wrinkle — worth calling out now.)
  - Entry points: pre-onboarding = a "Take the tour" button on the landing/register screen and as an optional step 0 of onboarding;
  post-onboarding = a "Replay tour" item (Settings + Help). Persist a per-role tourSeen flag on the user so we can auto-offer it
  once.
  - Feature-toggle reality: gyms can disable store/gallery/tournaments/etc. For an educational tour I'd show all capabilities with a
  small "if your gym enables this" note, rather than hiding them — otherwise new users never learn what's possible. (Open to your
  call.)

